@pfmoore It took me a lot of time to read this thread. TBH, I encountered this issue before myself. I kinda understand why the user raised the bug but I also understand your point of view: effectively virtualenv have no idea (or control) over what script it will be installed inside its bin directory.

Sadly it remains up to each script to implement the logic for being able to replicate activation tricks whenever this is needed, ansible being a very good example. Shortly I would advise against using any virtualenv installed tools without doing an activate first.

Other than this, looking at the proposed documentation change, I have nothing against it, it just describes more clear the behaviour, hopefully having less confusions in the future.

(Just ran into an issue with this again.)

As an alternative fix, that wouldn't change as much of the interface, how about if we only change the implementation of `held_offsets` so that it returns `-2` (ie `OffsetType.EARLIEST) when it holds `-1` internally? So

```python
    @property
    def held_offsets(self):
        """Return a map from partition id to held offset for each partition"""
        return {p.partition.id: (OffsetType.EARLIEST if p.last_offset_consumed == -1 
                                 else p.last_offset_consumed)
                for p in itervalues(self._partitions_by_id)}
```

If that makes sense, I'd propose this for 2.0.0.

