@sduskis FWIW, both of the failures in [CircleCI 6267](https://circleci.com/gh/GoogleCloudPlatform/google-cloud-python/6267) are 503s during `CreateTable` requests (one is in the setup for a column family test).

#5421 modified the system tests to ensure that they didn't share a common table name, which seems to have made the 503s go away.y working theory is that the same-name table created and deleted in an earlier test sometimes "hangs around" (like a ghost -- due to eventual consisency?), triggering the 503 error (which should maybe have been a 409?).

All but one of the failures in [CircleCI 6268](https://circleci.com/gh/GoogleCloudPlatform/google-cloud-python/6268) are likewise 503s during `CreateTable`.  The assertion error in the one is due to unexpected tables returned from `ListTables`: maybe related to the eventual consistency problem?

Thanks @mjpost , this is pretty convincing that we should use mxnet's topk for gpu contexts, and numpy's topk for cpu context (e.g. if `--use-cpu` is given on the translate CLI)! Would you be able to create a separate PR for this switch maybe?

On a related note, the mxnet topk function (https://github.com/awslabs/sockeye/blob/master/sockeye/utils.py#L284) still converts the topk results to numpy for unraveling the indices (getting the coordinates in the original `matrix` tensor. 
@sxjscience  do you think it would make sense to create a feature request to have such operator in mxnet? mshadow already seems to have it but it is not exposed to MXNet. I don't know how much work this would be but we would remove any dependency on Numpy in beam search here, and hence synchronization points between GPU and CPU due to no more `.asnumpy()` calls. This could give us another boost.

